    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Al). Stands occur on stabilized dunes at Nipomo Dunes.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-d, Bf-h). Stands occupy coastal bluffs and slopes in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), and bluffs and stabilized dunes on many of the Channel Islands. Inland stands on Santa Cruz Island occupy wind gaps with high fog drip. Island stands have greater species variation than do mainland ones. The island stands are especially rich in halophytes and herbaceous plants (Johnson and Rodriguez 2001). Individual stands described in Junak et al. (2007) differ in either having <i>Atriplex</i> spp. and <i>Suaeda taxifolia</i> or having <i>Claytonia perfoliata</i> and <i>Marah macrocarpus.</i></li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Mesembryanthemum crystallinum </i> and other ice plant taxa threaten island stands. <i>Carpobrotus edulis </i>and other ice plant taxa threaten mainland stands. Manual removal is less likely to disturb the native species. <i>Pennisetum setaceum, </i>an invasive grass (see description of this non-native type), grows in some stands in the Santa Monica Mountains and tends to overrun even very steep bluff faces in this area. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Associations</h4>
        
            
            <ul class="text">
                
                    <li>Coreopsis gigantea - Artemisia californica - Eriogonum cinereum [1]</li>
                
                    <li>Coreopsis gigantea / (Dudleya greenei) [2]</li>
                
                    <li>Coreopsis gigantea - Ericameria ericoides - Encelia californica [1]</li>
                
                    <li>Coreopsis gigantea - Lotus dendroideus [2]</li>
                
                    <li>Coreopsis gigantea - (Lycium californicum - Opuntia spp.) [2]</li>
                
            </ul>
        
    </div>

    
